pros:
-Their work in the field is amazing and transformational for those suffering from systematic and oppressive injustices;
-Pay and benefits are good for a non-profit;
-Daily prayer, quarterly prayer retreats, and they are trying to get better at staff care.

cons:
- Top-heavy and doesn’t listen well to the field offices, makes decisions based on ideologies at headquarters (in DC) that negatively affect the work and resource allocation to the field;
- Doesn’t value the contributions of mid-level employees;
- Significant issues with people taking credit for your work and using it to boost their own value within the org.;
- Feels very petty and as though there is a lot of behind your back talking and a lot of favoritism;
- They don’t like to hear the truth about the reality of what’s going on, and it creates a negative environment where people are afraid to speak up—honesty is not rewarded or valued;
- Agree with the review that noted rampant favoritism, “good ole boys club” mentality, and those that “play the (IJM) game” are the only ones that seem to advance.
